        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-06-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-06-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="126"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d126">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Prime Minister</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Churchill</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to President <persName type="to"
                            >Roosevelt</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="90" type="source" xml:id="d126fn90">Copy of telegram obtained from the
                        Franklin D. Roosevelt Library, Hyde Park, N.Y. Paraphrase sent to the
                        Secretary of State by President Roosevelt on June 30.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-14">14 June
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>703. 1. Your number 560:<note n="91" xml:id="d126fn91">Dated June 12, <ref
                            target="#pg_121">p. 121</ref>.</note> I am deeply grateful to you for
                    your reply to my number 700. I have asked the Foreign Secretary to convey the
                    information to Monsieur Molotov and to make it clear that the reason for the
                    three months limit is in order that we should not prejudge the question of
                    establishing post-war spheres of influence.</p>
                <p>[Here follow comments by Prime Minister Churchill on Italian affairs, the visit
                    of General Charles de Gaulle to France and military government in France, and
                    the Prime Minister’s visit to the Normandy beachhead.]</p>
            </div>
